Yes, you can use Tailwind CSS with Preact, as Tailwind is a utility-first CSS framework and does not depend on the underlying JavaScript framework being used. 

To use Tailwind with Preact, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the Tailwind CSS library using npm:
```
npm install tailwindcss
```

2. Create a `tailwind.config.js` file in your project's root directory to customize the default configuration if needed:
```
// Example tailwind.config.js file contents
module.exports = {
  purge: [],
  theme: {
    extend: {},
  },
  variants: {},
  plugins: [],
}
```

3. Create a CSS file to import and configure Tailwind. For example, create a file named `styles.css` in your project's `src` directory and include the following:
```
/* Import the Tailwind CSS library */
@import 'tailwindcss/base';
@import 'tailwindcss/components';
@import 'tailwindcss/utilities';

/* Add any additional custom styles */
```

4. Import the CSS file into your Preact app. For example, in your main `index.js` file, you can add the following line to import the CSS:
```
import './styles.css';
```

Once these steps are completed, you should be able to use Tailwind utility classes in your Preact components, such as `class="bg-gray-100 p-4"` to set the background color to light gray and add padding to an element.

To launch your default browser automatically when you run `yarn dev` in VS Code, you can use the `open` command with the URL of the local development server in your project's `package.json` file.

Here's an example of what you can add to your `package.json` file:

```
{
  "name": "my-project",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "my-start-command && open http://localhost:3000"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "my-package": "^1.0.0"
  }
}
```

Note that `my-start-command` should be replaced with the actual start command you use for your project.

The `open` command will open the URL `http://localhost:3000` (or whichever port your local development server is running on) in your default browser when you run `yarn dev`.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions.
